</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="75" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,152,395]" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,297,323]" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Remarks.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[322,437,296,322]" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Holotypes</typeStatus>
and other types could not be located. Description and remarks from 
<bibRefCitation author="Maindron, M." box="[1203,1395,296,323]" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" pagination="15 - 16" refId="ref20376" refString="Maindron, M. (1906) Description d'une nouvelle espece de Pheropsophus et remarques sur ce genre. Bulletin de la Societe entomologique de France, 1906, 15 - 16." type="journal article" year="1906">Maindron (1906)</bibRefCitation>
are given. Very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1876" box="[399,543,332,358]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Pheropsophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aptinoides">
<emphasis box="[399,543,332,358]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">P. aptinoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by longer form, longer and slender pronotum, completely black legs and antennae, intervals of elytral striations much rougher. It is endemic to Indo-Burma hotspot of biodiversity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
